version: 1
display_name: VCFV-9X-000214 - Virtual machines (VMs) must remove unneeded floppy devices.
global_description: |-
  Ensure no device is connected to a virtual machine if it is not required. For example, floppy, serial, and parallel ports are rarely used for virtual machines in a data center environment, and CD/DVD drives are usually connected only temporarily during software installation.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFV-9X-000214
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000480-VMM-002000
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_vm:
    type: custom
    desc: Virtual machines (VMs) must remove unneeded floppy devices.
    control_id: VCFV-9X-000214
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      Floppy drives are no longer visible through the vSphere Client and must be configured via the Application Programming Interface (API) or PowerCLI.

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host or vCenter server, run the following command:

      Get-VM | Get-FloppyDrive | Select Parent, Name, ConnectionState

      If a virtual machine has a floppy drive connected, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      Ensure no device is connected to a virtual machine if it is not required. For example, floppy, serial, and parallel ports are rarely used for virtual machines in a data center environment, and CD/DVD drives are usually connected only temporarily during software installation.
    remediation: |-
      Floppy drives are no longer visible through the vSphere Client and must be configured via the Application Programming Interface (API) or PowerCLI.

      The VM must be powered off to remove a floppy drive.

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host or vCenter server, run the following command:

      Get-VM "VM Name" | Get-FloppyDrive | Remove-FloppyDrive
